{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170847/1946062701/0363.xml":{"full_text":"MARKET SLUMPS\nSLIGHTLY AFTER\nPESSIMISTIC DAY\nRailroads Disappointed by\nICC Increase Buyers\u2019\nStrike Talk May Mean\n1 roubles lor Labor\nIVall Nlreid Correspondence\nTill* l{epubllciiii\nNew York, Juin> 25 Sellitit? came\ninto the market for industrial stocks\nthp first hour and continued to the\nclose with the average for this group\nending down 1.02. Evidently holders\nof railroad stocks are disappointed\nover the small interim increase just\ngranted by the ICC in freight rates\nas of July 1. Kails sold off throughout\nthe session, ending down 1.05. which\non a percentage basis is a much,\nlarger decline than occurred in in-1\ndust rials.\n'-id' w.\u00bb Southern ra\nway voiced the opinion of railway ex-j\neuuiivea when he declared today that'\nthe increase in freight rates is not!\nenough to cover increased overhead:\nthat the increase would add $4.00.000\nto his company\u2019s gross revenue for\nthe last half of this year, hut that\nthe recent further advance in rail\nroad wages would add $19,000,000 to\nthe year's operating expenses re-,\nserve: that the increase in the sell-!\ning price of coal to offset the in-j\ncrease in miners\u2019 wages would add\nanother $2,000,000 to the year's over\nhead.\nWhen the market opened this\nmorning Wall streets information on\nthe results of last night's session\nof the Senate-House conferees for\na showdown on the price control ex\ntension bill was that the administra\ntion was going to get far less than\nit had asked for but that it had less\nto fear in the way of threatened\nelimination of government control.\nRemoval of price control by the OPA\non such important items a\u00ab meat,\nlivestock, butter and other dairy prod\nucts, poultry, petroleum, cigarets and\ntobacco was stricken from the bill\nbut OPA\u2019s power to say when ceiling\nprices would be removed was yanked\naway by agreement that such power\nshould he placed in the hands of a\nboard of three members to be ap\npointed by President Truman and\nconfirmed by the Senate. Many of\nthe revised clauses in the bill were\nwritten specifically to force further\nadvances in selling prices.\nFrom its early morning information\nfrom Washington Wall street con\ncluded that if the bill were passed in\nthe form agreed upon last night and\nproperly administered, the country\ncould work 'out of the mess it is in.\ngrowing out of the government\u2019s re\nconversion wage-price program. Ac\ntion of the market, however, indicated\nthat, in view of the administration\u2019s\nrecord in handling the reconversion\nproblem since the war ended the mid\ndle of last August, there was uncer\ntainty over future government price\ncontrol.\nWhat Wall street saw in the\namended price control bill as it stood\nbefore the opening of the market this\nmorning was that the OPA was to\nbe continued under another name, the\nproposed decontrol board: that this\nboard would hang on to price con\ntrol even after production of separate\nitems of consumer goods had balanced\nwith demand, as for example, the OPA\nhas in delaying elimination of ceiling\nprices on petroleum long after there\nwas any need for ceiling prices that\nin the meantime prices of consumer\ngoods would continue to rise because\nof the new' clauses written in the bill\nspecifically to force a rise in selling\nprices.\nWall street\u2019s considered opinion is\nthat the worst phase today for the\ngeneral business outlook is the wide\nspread talk of a buyers\u2019 strike, the\nlatest development, in that direction\nbeing today\u2019s dispatch from Washing\nton Mooting Senator Taylor (D-Jda),\nas calling for \"a buyers\u2019 strike to\nmake prices come down.\u201d \u201cThis is\nthe time, he. declared, \"for buyers t.o j\nbegin waiting for a market that will j\nbe advantageous to them\u201d; that \u201cnow\nis the time consumers can make j\nthemselves felt if they retrain from;\nbuying at high prices. They can;\nmake prices come down.\u201d\nAs some people in the financial;\ndistrict see it the worst of such\ntalk as the foregoing is that it does j\nnot indicate an understanding of the\nsituation and outlook. A strike on\nthe part of the consuming public\nagainst high prices suggests volun\ntary action. Doubtless many people\nas a protest against high prices are\ntoday doing without things they could\nafford to buy but a buyers\u2019 strike\ncuch as started in May, 1920. follow\ning postwar inflation was the result\nof inability to pay the high prices\nbeing demanded. With h further\nadvance in prices, many people in\nthe socalled white collar group of\nfrom 35,000.000 to 40.000,000 con\nsumers will not be able to pay their\npart of the bill created by the ad\nvance in wages of some 14,000.000\nmember*? of organized labor. When a j\nlarge number of consumers are forced\nout of the market because of high\nprices, the result is curtailed demand\nand growing unemployment in in\ndustries producing consumer good**.;\nThat is when deflation begins to\nlake the place of inflation.\nin Its monthly bank letter the!\nGuaranty Trust Co. here says, \u201d'The j\nmost traffic feature of the strike;\nwave is its cost lo workers them\nselves. Hundreds of millions of dol\nlars iii wages have been lost. Recon\nversion has been delayed for months\nwith increased danger of the infla- j\ntion thaL would cost labor incal\nculable sums, not only because the\ncost of living in inflationary periods j\noutruns the rise in wage rates but;\nalso because such periods are fol\nlowed by violent reactions resulting;\nin mass unemployment.\u201d\nWorkers in a strongly unionized\nIndustry may by striking achieve a\nwage increase, it is pointed out, but j\n\u201cthe increase immediately sets up\nforces that tend to nullify its bene- j\nfits. Profits in industry tend to de-\ndine with the rise in costs: it be\ncomes less worth while for pro- 1\nducers to employ labor and em-\nploy men t opportunities decrease.\nEven under the very exceptional\nconditions of demand that exists to\nday. there is increasing discussion\nof the possibilities of a \u2018buyers\u2019j\nstrike\u2019 against rising prices and\nlower quality.\u201d R- L. BARN'UM.\nCORPORATIONS IN U. S.\nTO SPEND TWO BILLION\nPhiladelphia, June 24\u2014(AP) Ex\npenditures of 4merlesn business for\nnew plants and equipment are ex\npected to total approximately $2,100,-\n000,000 dur'ng the second quarter of\nthis year, the Securities and Exchange\ncommission and the department of\ncommerce reported Jointly today.\nThe amount compares with $2,-\n100.000,000 both in the first quarter\nof 1946 and the last quarter of |940.\nThe total includes approximately\n$2,200,000,000 spent hy corporations,\nthe remainder by unincorporated bus\niness. Agriculture ts not Included,\nButter, Egg Market\nChicago. June 24\u2014(AFV\u2014(U8t)Ai Tha\nbutter market was Arm and unchanged a*\nOP A ceiling price? (bulk in fiber boxes, s\u00bb\npound): A.\\ 9.'? score 57; A 92 score o\u00ab4.\nB fin acora .Vil%. Kgs? were steady to firm:\nlarge Vo. j ami 2 extra* 38-39.t*: Xc. 5 and\n4 extras .'>6-38; medium extras 38.3-34.\n*Unuatd\u00ab U current receipt? 32-33.25;\ndirt tea 30.3-51.5, and checks 30-51.\nFINANCIAL\nDEMAND FOR GLENMORE\nALMOST DOUBLES PRICE\nLarge Bids Mark the First\nPublic Sale of Class 'B'\nCommon Stock\nNew York, June 25 (AH \u2014Class\n'TV common stock of Glenmore Dis\ntilleries Co. almost doubled in price\nafter going on sale for the first time\nthis morning at $lB a share.\nlju.te today the stock was quoted t\n$13.50 bid, $34.50 offered in the over\nthe-counter market.\nTremendous demand developed for\nth issue, soon after* a banking syndi\ncate headed by (11 ore Forgan Co.\noffered 125,000 shares in the first pub\nlic sale of the company's securities.\nAs much as $33 a share was bid\neven before the syndicate announced\ndosing of its books.\nSELECTED STOCKS\nTRY FOR RECOVERY\nContinued Talk of Buyers\u2019\nStrike Invokes Caution as\nRails Seem Depressed by\nFreight Rate Action\nj New York, June 24 \u2014(AP) Se\nlevied stocks continued to lean to\nward recovery today while many mar\nket leaders, paced by most rails,\nshifted to the posing track.\nRoth bids and offerings were light,\nfrom the start. Volume was aided,\nthough, by sizable blocks of low\nquoted utilities such as Common\nwealth Southern which appeared,\nat the 1.-st, in a 25.800-share transac\ntion.* up Vi at $5.37. With scattered\nexceptions, gains and losses ranged\nfrom fractions to a point or so at\nl he close. Transfers of 990,000\nshares compared with 1,310.000 on\nFriday\u2019s rally.\nBrokerage clients again exhibited\nconsiderable caution pending enact\nment of price-control legislation. Talk\nof a buyers\u2019 strike., both in stocks\nand durable, goods, persisted as a re\nstraining influence. Some placed\nthis deflationary phase after l-abor\nday and others believed if might not\neventuate until 1947. Dividends and\nearnings inspired a certain amount\nof bidding. Carriers seemed de\npressed by the freight rate boost\nwhich transportation circles thought\nvas insufficient to cover mounting\ncons.\nThe Associated Press 60-stock com\nposite was unchanged at 78.8. In\ndustrials were up .2, rails off .3 and\nutilities unchanged. Of 962 issues\nregistering, 435 rose and 359 fell.\nBonds did better at the finish al\nlhough many faltered. \\t Chicago\ngrains were at ceilings. Colton ad\nvanced 40 cents to SL. a bale.\nIn the curb Srcrchi Bros, stiffened\non an earnings statement and split\nup proposal. Larger dividends lifted\nPhans Tire ana Kabaeker Stores i\nfractionally. South Penn Oil and,\nCalalin were in demand. Turnover\nhere was 360.000 shares against 440,-\n000 in tne preceding session.\nOPA INCREASES PRICE\nOF MIDWEST IRON ORE\nWashington. .June 24 (AP) \u2014An\nincrease of 50 cents a ton in the;\nprice of iron ore from Minnesota,\nWisconsin and Michigan was an\nnounced by OPA today.\nEffective at once, toe increase was\npermitted to meet the legal require\nment that ceiling prices afford an in\ndustry a profit equal to its 1936-39\ncate of return.\nThe wage increase of 18Vs cent,* an\nhour, granted by all merchant ore\nproducers in the Lake Superior dis\ntrict in January, and reduced volume\nof operation, were the factors neces\nsitating the price boosr. OPA said,\nFORD FARM TRACTORS\nGET OPA PRICE BOOST\nWashington. .Tune 24 (AP)\nOPA today granted an increase of\n$127.16 in the manufacturers' price\ni ceilings on farm tractors produced by\nthe Ford Motor Co.\nThe Harry Ferguson Co., distributor\niof Ford tractors, received a \"pro\nportionate increase.\u201d OPA said, which\nresults in its list price advancing\nfrom $828..81 to $966.21.\nOPA said the price boost would\ncompensate for higher labor and\nmaterials cost.\nDIVIDEND STATEMENTS\nVertlentes-CamaatM*.'\nX*w York. June. 2 4\u2014(AT*) \u2014D\u2018 reciors \"f\nVertienis-Camaguey Sugar Co. rt-uiblod the\nd vidend on the common siock by declar\ning a ouarterly payment of 50 r-enia a share,\npayable August 10 stix-k of record July\n15. Previously 50 cants a share had been\npaid semiannual!.'.\nHecht 0.\nHe\u00abhi Co. director* today declared a 40\nper cem dividend on common stock, pay\nable July M 10 holders of record July S.\nPrevious quarterly payment* were Ift cents.\nBeatrice Foods\nChicago. June 24\u2014(AP)-Beatrice Foods,\nCo. today announced the dividend rate on\nit* .proposed new issue of par con-\nvertible preferred stock would h l 1 net\ncent. New preferred will be offered hold\ners ,of the presently 0111.-landing $4.25 pre\nferred stock on a xhare-fnr-share basis.\nFleetroluv orp.\nNew York. June 21- (AP: Directors of\nKlectroux Corp. today declared nn interim\ndividend of 50 (\u201ctits a capital share, payable\nAugust 2. to st<K-k of record July 2. Previous\npayments we 25 cents each in February\nand May of l|.s year.\nAmerican Mutual\nBoston. June 21 A dividend of 20 per cent\npayable on all policies expiring during the\nperiod September 1. 1946 to September 30.\n1946 has been declared by the American\nMutual Liability Insurance (10. litis is\nAmerican Mutual s 694th consecutive dividend\nof 20 per cent or more to its policyholders.\nHousehold Finn uce\nNew York. .June 13\u2014(AP)\u2014-Di\nrector* of Household Finance Corp.\ndeclared a dividend of 40 cents a\nshare on common .stock payable July\n1% to holders of record .June 29. Pre\nvious payments were 35 cents a share\neach quarter.\nCleveland Trust\nA dividend of $4 a share payable\nJune 25 to stock of record June 15\nwas declared by directors of th:\nCleveland Trust Co. in 1945 payments\nof 33 June 25 an<r $3.50 December 24\nwere made.\nPressed Steel far\nPressed Steel Car Co. directors took\nno action today on a dividend for\ncommon stock, on which they had de\nclared 25 cent dividends in previous\nquarters. They declared the regular\nquarterly dividend of 56 cents on\npreferred stock, payable July 1 to\nholders of record June 24.\nBankers Securities Corp.\nDirectors of Bankers Securities\n(\u2019orp. of Philadelphia declared a divi\ndend of $4 a share on outstanding\nparticipating preferred stock, pay\nable July 15 to holders of record June\ni 29. The company paid $2.50 each in\nj December and June. 1945.\nTextron. Inc.\nI Payment on July 1 of the quarterly\ndividend on the 5 per cent convertible\npreferred stock of Textron, inc.. has\nbeen voted by the board of directors.\nRoyal IJttle. president of Textron, an\nnoun red today. Payment will be\nmade to stockholders of record as of\nthe close of business June 13.\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN* SPRINGFIELD. MASS.: THURSDAY, JUNE 27, 1946\nNEW YORK STOCK MARKET\nSale of Stocks\nNew York Stork \u00ab\u00ab*li\u00bbbw HXO.OOII\nNew York Curb (irhangn 310,000\nitoNion Stork exchange 17,101\nNet\nHole* in 100\u2019a High l\u00abow Close Chg.\n11 Abbott Lab 72 71 Vi 71' 4 V 4\n.30 Do pf 112 112 112\n2 Acme .St I 4