ral Power Commission\nRefuses His Continuation\nWith Three Utilities\nWtiAhinirfon. Itine 24\u2014(AF% \u2014L*o T\nIf!rowle.v, formerly promlnenr in tr\u00bboj\nera! Pow*!* rommission today from j\nf onllnulnjr a a a director for threr\nprivately owned public utilities.\nCrowley, now president and board\nj chairman of Standard Gam and Klee*\ntrie Corp. of Chicago, was denied\nauthority to continue as a director of\njthe Wisconsin Public Service Corp..\nof Milwaukee: the Louisville. Ky..\n'Gas and Klee trie Co., and the Du\n-1 Queane Light Co., of Pittsburg.\nThe FPC grounded its action on a\nI section of the fed eral power act for\n-1 bidding anyone to he simultaneously\nan officer or director of more than,\n<\u00bbne public utility or a utility and a\nfinancial inatltuUon marketing ut; I*\ntiea securities. The act. however,\nan ev e >tinn, for in\nwhich it t\u00ab shown* that \u201cn\u00ab*ifher puh\n|lie nor private interest* will he ad*\nveraely affected.\u2019\nCrowley also wax forbidden by (he\n1 CPC to serve as chairman of the\nDueucane company\u2019s executive and\ni finance committee.\nSLUMP OVERCOME\nAS BUYERS RETURN\nStock Market Gets Back On\nIts Feet After Thursday\u2019s\nTumble\u2014Many Customers\n1 Still Stand Aside\nNew York, June 21\u2014(AP) \u2014The\nj stock market, while still exceptionally\nj \u2018thin got back on it* seer. today\nafter Thursday 's slump as buyers re\nturned with the Idea it had been\n[oversold and was in a much healthier\n[technical shape.\nThere was some letdown after an\nimproved start bur rails, steel*,\nmotors, rubbers and assorted blue\nchips came forward in the final hour\nwith volume expanding. .While numer\nous losers persisted, gains of frae\ntions to 3 or more points were well\n|in the majority at the close. Trans\nj fers of 1.340,000 shares compared with\nj L 310,000 the day before and were the\nlargest since May 29.\nMany customers stood aside or\nlightened commitments pending price\ncorn rol legislation and an expected\n[freight rale boost. Talk of a \"buyers\u2019\nstrike\u2019\u2019 in stocks again was a cau\ntionary influence, as was some skepti\nl cism over business prospects.\nThe Associated Press 60-stock com\nposite. with the aid of a few wide\nI jumpers, was up .7 of a point at 78.8.\nOf 1003 issues registering, 500 rose\nand 339 fell.\nBonds were irregularly lower. Cot-\nT ort was up S 3 to 90 cents a bale. At\nChicago grains remained at ceilings.\nHigher in the curb were Textron.\nHoward Stores. Middle West Corn..\nPan tepee. Cities Service and Electric\nBond Share. Turnover here was\n440.000 shares versus 540.000 yester\nday\nGAR WOOD PURCHASES\nFORMER BENDIX PLANT\nNew York, June 20 \u2014(AP) \u2014Pur-\nchase of the former Bendix plant in\nWayne. Mich., from the War Assets\nadministration was announced today\nby Gar Wood Industries, inc.\nJohn J. Bergen, chairman of Gar\nWood, said the purchase was made in\norder \u00bbo meet the sharply increased\ndemand for the company's products\nand to expand present manufactur\ning facilities.\nThe company w ill Transfer all of its\nDetroit operations to the new site\nwith the exception of its body plant.\nGar Wood will manufacture in the\nnew plant hydraulic hoists. steel\nbodies, winches, cranes and derricks\nfor motor trucks: hydraulic- systems\nand attachments for bulldozers,\nscrapers, and other tractor equip\nment; heating units and ventilating\nfans.\nOPA Boosts Ceilings\nOn Cereal Wheat Bran\nWashington. June 20 \u2014(AP) \u2014OPA\ntoday raised producers\u2019 ceiling prices\n$lO a ton for wheat bran used in\nbreakfast ceteals. The agency said\nthis increase, effective immediately,\nhad been inadvertently omitted from\na list of grains and feeds for which\nprices were last May 13. The\nhigher price' w-jll have no effect at\nthis time, on retail ceilings of wheat\nbran breakfast cereals. OPA said.\nSEC MATTERS\nKlwtrir Rond ami Share\nPh ladtlph a. June 24 I.AP\u00bb Klectrir\nR\"nd and Sharp Co fl'-d :-+\u00ab